# {{name}}

Rosette photonic design project. Python scripts in `designs/` produce GDSII layout files.

## ALWAYS read the reference files before coding

Before writing or modifying any Rosette code, read these files:

- `.rosette/api.pyi` -- complete typed API (source of truth for all classes and functions)
- `rosette.toml` -- project config, layer definitions (named layers), DRC rules, DFM config

Your training data may be outdated -- these files match your installed version.

## ALWAYS build then check

A design is not complete until it passes checks. After every build, run checks and fix any violations before presenting the result:

```
uv run rosette build designs/foo.py
uv run rosette check designs/foo.py --json
```

Always pass `--json`: checks then emit a single JSON object on stdout — read `passed` directly and use each violation's `bbox` (in microns) to locate the problem, instead of parsing prose that may reword. A passing build only means the GDS was written -- it does NOT mean the design is correct. `rosette check` catches DRC violations (min width, spacing, overlap), unconnected ports, width mismatches, and bend radius violations.

## Key conventions

- Designs must export a `design` variable (a `Cell` instance)
- Use `load_layer_map()` to get layers from rosette.toml -- never hardcode layer numbers
- The package is `librosette` (installed via `uv add librosette`, imported as `rosette`)
- To inspect a design visually, `uv run rosette shot designs/foo.py` renders a PNG (plus a sidecar JSON with the world<->pixel transform) to `.rosette/snapshots/`

